The most recent data shows that 70% of women in Kosovo have an education beyond basic primary education, and men are just as likely as women to have done so. In 2011, 61% were married, but nearly half (43%) of those married did so before reaching 20.

Half of women who sought an abortion during 2011-12 had been trying to prevent or delay getting pregnant, said Nezira Ademi-Saranovic, of the Kosovo Women's Network Enterprise. The number of abortion requests has grown during these years due to an "earlier sexual debut and less access to contraceptives," said Ademi-Saranovic.

The series of amendments introduced in 2001 to the Law on Healthcare system, promulgated later in 2002 and regulating the use of reproductive technologies, stated that legal abortions would be considered free of charge under the Healthcare system provided that three grounds were met: pregnancy would represent a high threat to the life and health of the woman; the pregnancy resulted from a criminal act; and the pregnancy was not intended.
